ðŸ§© Step 2 â€“ Inserting Documents
ðŸ‘‰ Single Insert
db.students.insertOne({ name: "Rohan", age: 20, course: "IT", marks: 85, hobbies: ["cricket", "coding"] })

ðŸ‘‰ Batch Insert
db.students.insertMany([
  { name: "Ravina", age: 21, course: "CS", marks: 92, hobbies: ["music", "reading"] },
  { name: "Arjun", age: 22, course: "IT", marks: 78, hobbies: ["football", "gaming"] },
  { name: "Sneha", age: 20, course: "ENTC", marks: 88, hobbies: ["painting", "dancing"] },
  { name: "Rahul", age: 21, course: "CS", marks: 67, hobbies: ["coding", "music"] }
])


âœ… Insert validation
MongoDB automatically validates field types during insert (e.g., strings, numbers, arrays).
You can also add validation rules later using db.createCollection() with a schema.

ðŸ§© Step 3 â€“ Removing Documents
ðŸ‘‰ Remove one document
db.students.deleteOne({ name: "Rahul" })

ðŸ‘‰ Remove multiple
db.students.deleteMany({ course: "ENTC" })

ðŸ§© Step 4 â€“ Updating Documents
ðŸ‘‰ Replace entire document
db.students.replaceOne({ name: "Ravina" }, { name: "Ravina", age: 22, course: "CS", marks: 95 })

ðŸ‘‰ Update specific fields using $set
db.students.updateOne({ name: "Rohan" }, { $set: { marks: 90 } })

ðŸ‘‰ Update multiple
db.students.updateMany({ course: "IT" }, { $inc: { marks: 5 } })

ðŸ‘‰ Upsert (update if exists, else insert)
db.students.updateOne({ name: "John" }, { $set: { course: "IT", marks: 80 } }, { upsert: true })

ðŸ‘‰ Return updated document
db.students.findOneAndUpdate({ name: "Rohan" }, { $set: { marks: 93 } }, { returnDocument: "after" })

ðŸ§© Step 5 â€“ 10+ Queries
1ï¸âƒ£ Find all documents
